05667nam a22007215i 9780822376538DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223765387 a10.1515/97808223765382doi  a(DE-B1597)553210  a(OCoLC)868992389  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1075b.G463 2014eb 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a331.4b2300aGendering the Recession :bMedia and Culture in an Age of Austerity /cYvonne Tasker, Diane Negra. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b24 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Gender and Recessionary Culture -- tOne. Escaping the Recession? The New Vitality of the Woman Worker -- tTwo. "Latina Wisdom" in "Postrace" Recession Media -- tThree. "We Are All Workers": Economic Crisis, Masculinity, and the American Working Class -- tFour. What Julia Knew: Domestic Labor in the Recession-Era Chick Flick -- tFive. Dressed for Economic Distress: Blogging and the "New" Pleasures of Fashion -- tSix. The (Re)possession of the American Home: Negative Equity, Gender Inequality, and the Housing Crisis Horror Story -- tSeven. House and Home: Structuring Absences in Post-Celtic Tiger Documentary -- tEight. "Stuck between Meanings": Recession-Era Print Fictions of Crisis Masculinity -- tNine. Fairy Jobmother to the Rescue: Postfeminism and the Recessionary Cultures of Reality TV -- tTen. How Long Can the Party Last? Gendering the European Crisis on Reality TV -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis timely, necessary collection of essays provides feminist analyses of a recession-era media culture characterized by the reemergence and refashioning of familiar gender tropes, including crisis masculinity, coping women, and postfeminist self-renewal. Interpreting media forms as diverse as reality television, financial journalism, novels, lifestyle blogs, popular cinema, and advertising, the contributors reveal gendered narratives that recur across media forms too often considered in isolation from one another. They also show how, with a few notable exceptions, recession-era popular culture promotes affective normalcy and transformative individual enterprise under duress while avoiding meaningful critique of the privileged white male or the destructive aspects of Western capitalism. By acknowledging the contradictions between political rhetoric and popular culture, and between diverse screen fantasies and lived realities, Gendering the Recession helps to make sense of our postboom cultural moment.Contributors. Sarah Banet-Weiser, Hamilton Carroll, Hannah Hamad, Anikó Imre, Suzanne Leonard, Isabel Molina-Guzmán, Sinéad Molony, Elizabeth Nathanson, Diane Negra, Tim Snelson, Yvonne Tasker, Pamela Thoma   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009. 0aSex rolexEconomic aspects. 0aWomen in development. 0aWomenxEmployment. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aImre, Anikó, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNegra, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNathanson, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Hamilton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamad, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolina-Guzmán, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNegra, Diane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThoma, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v